      <example id="exam-00008">
      <title>Applying Similar Triangles</title>
      <exercise id="exer-00015">
      <problem id="prob-00015">
      <para id="para-00060">A person who is 5 feet tall is standing 50 feet away from the base of a tree (<link target-id="fig-00017" document="m00127">Figure 10.87</link>). The tree casts a 57-foot shadow. The person casts a 7-foot shadow. What is the height of the tree?</para>
      <figure id="fig-00017">
      <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
      <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Figure_10_03_UN017.png"/>
      </media>
      <caption/>
      </figure>
      </problem>
      <solution id="sol-00008">
      <para id="para-00061">The bigger triangle includes a tree at side <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>x</mi></math> and the smaller triangle includes the person at the side labeled 5 ft. These two triangles are similar because the smaller triangle fits inside the larger triangle at the smallest angle. It would fit inside the larger triangle at either of the other two angles as well. That all angles are equal is one of the criteria for similar triangles, so we can solve using proportions:
       <equation id="eq-00013" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mtable columnspacing="0.3em"><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>57</mn></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mn>5</mn><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>57</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mn>7</mn><mi>x</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mfrac><mrow><mn>285</mn></mrow><mn>7</mn></mfrac></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>40.7</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></equation></para>
      <para id="para-00062" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The tree is 40.7 feet tall.</para>
      </solution>
      </exercise>
      </example>
